statement:
The code below has a data race. Run it mentally (or with `-race`) to identify the problem, then fix it by adding a `sync.RWMutex` to `Counter` and protecting the `Inc` and `Value` methods appropriately.

```go
type Counter struct {
    n int
}

func (c *Counter) Inc() {
    c.n++
}

func (c *Counter) Value() int {
    return c.n
}

func main() {
    c := &Counter{}
    var wg sync.WaitGroup
    for i := 0; i < 1000; i++ {
        wg.Add(1)
        go func() {
            defer wg.Done()
            c.Inc()
        }()
    }
    wg.Wait()
    fmt.Println(c.Value())
}
```

solution:
```go
type Counter struct {
    mu sync.RWMutex
    n  int
}

func (c *Counter) Inc() {
    c.mu.Lock()
    defer c.mu.Unlock()
    c.n++
}

func (c *Counter) Value() int {
    c.mu.RLock()
    defer c.mu.RUnlock()
    return c.n
}
```

`Inc` writes `c.n`, so it needs the exclusive write lock (`Lock`). `Value` only reads, so it uses the shared read lock (`RLock`). With 1000 goroutines incrementing, the final value will consistently be 1000.

```go
func (s *ServerPool) GetNextPeer() *Backend {
    next := s.NextIndex()
    l := len(s.backends) + next
    for i := next; i < l; i++ {
        idx := i % len(s.backends)
        if s.backends[idx].IsAlive() {
            if i != next {
                atomic.StoreUint64(&s.current, uint64(idx))
            }
            return s.backends[idx]
        }
    }
    return nil
}
```

Now every read of the `Alive` field goes through the `RWMutex`, and `SetAlive` (called by health checks) uses the write lock. There are no more data races around backend liveness.
